            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 57-year-old man living in the Czech Republic who has noticed needing to urinate more often and feeling unusually thirsty over recent months, describing a bothersome pattern of polyuria and increased drinking that fits common clinical findings in type 2 diabetes mellitus [SNOMED:E11.9]. He says the thirst is especially noticeable during the workday, when he keeps a water bottle close by and looks for restrooms more often than he used to [SNOMED:E11.9].\n\nHe works a steady daytime job and lives with his wife; his adult children visit on weekends. Outside work, {patientName} enjoys practical, quiet routines such as walking around his neighborhood, tending a small garden, and watching football with friends. He appears mildly overweight but not acutely ill, converses normally, and is mainly concerned that the frequent urination and thirst are disrupting sleep and daily comfort [SNOMED:E11.9].\n\nSocially, he remains active and independent, but he has started avoiding longer car trips and outdoor activities unless he knows where toilets are available because of the urinary frequency [SNOMED:E11.9]. He denies dramatic or unusual symptoms and presents as someone seeking straightforward advice after persistent everyday symptoms became hard to ignore. His goals are to control his blood sugar, reduce the polyuria, and feel less driven by thirst through the day [SNOMED:E11.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:c56ba07f-00cf-4e56-b1e9-c90ae1c3721c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports a gradual onset of frequent urination and increased thirst, with symptoms becoming more noticeable over the last several months [SNOMED:E11.9]. He has not had prior diabetic complications, and there is no history suggesting unusual comorbid conditions; this is consistent with a presentation of type 2 diabetes mellitus without complications. He has not required prior hospitalization for hyperglycemia or hypoglycemia.\n\nLifestyle-wise, {patientName} has a mostly sedentary work routine and acknowledges that his diet has often included large portions and regular bread-based meals, which is a plausible background for type 2 diabetes in a man of this age. He does not describe recurrent hypoglycemia, neuroglycopenia, or other atypical features that would suggest rare alternate explanations discussed in the evidence [PMID:34583764]. He has no known chronic endocrine disorder such as diabetes insipidus; however, persistent polyuria in diabetes should always be interpreted in relation to blood glucose control because other polyuric disorders can rarely coexist [PMID:29659364, PMID:38429969]."
          }
        ]
      }
